<% content_for :title, @mtitle %>
<% content_for :meta_description, @mdescription %>

<!-- Hero Section -->
<section class="py-5" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f8f9fa 0%, #e9ecef 100%);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
      <div class="col-lg-10 text-center">
        <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold mb-3">Buying a Property in the Canary Islands: The "Tourist Use" Legal Trap You Must Avoid</h1>
        <h2 class="h5 text-muted mb-4">Protecting Your Investment in Tenerife, Gran Canaria, Lanzarote, and Fuerteventura</h2>
        
        <div class="ratio ratio-16x9 mb-4 shadow-sm rounded overflow-hidden">
          <iframe
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/5XAROjYLqy0"
            title="Don't Buy Property in the Canaries Until You Watch This!"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
            loading="lazy"></iframe>
        </div>

        <div class="d-flex flex-column flex-sm-row gap-3 justify-content-center mt-4">
          <a href="#" data-bs-toggle="modal" data-bs-target="#contactModal" class="btn btn-lg rounded-pill px-4" style="background-color: #b39c84; border-color: #b39c84; color: white;">
            Secure My Conveyancing
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Article Content -->
<section class="py-5">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
      <div class="col-lg-8">
        <p class="lead mb-4">
          Are you looking at <strong>buying a property in Tenerife</strong>, <strong>investing in Gran Canaria</strong>, or finding a <strong>holiday home in Lanzarote</strong>? While the market is thriving, many international buyers are unknowingly walking into a legal minefield. In many of the most popular <strong>tourist areas in the Canary Islands</strong>, owning the title deed does not always mean you have the legal right to live in your own home.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
          My name is <strong>Olivier Roper</strong>, a lawyer and MBA specializing in <strong>Canary Islands property conveyancing</strong>. With over 15 years of experience and a unique background as a <strong>former Town Hall Counselor (Head of Business Licensing and Housing)</strong>, I provide my clients with an "insider" perspective on the complex urban planning laws that govern the islands.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">The Reality of "Suelo Turístico" (Touristic Land)</h2>
        <p class="mb-4">
          Whether you are <strong>buying an apartment in Las Américas (Tenerife)</strong>, a <strong>bungalow in Maspalomas (Gran Canaria)</strong>, or a <strong>villa in Playa Blanca (Lanzarote)</strong>, you must check the land classification.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          Large sections of these coastal regions are classified as <strong>Land for Touristic Use</strong>. Under the <strong>Canarian Tourism Act</strong>, properties on this land are legally "tourist units." This triggers the <strong>Principle of Unity of Exploitation</strong>, which can lead to:
        </p>
        <ul class="mb-4">
          <li><strong>Fines of up to €30,000</strong> for using a tourist unit as a permanent residence.</li>
          <li><strong>Compulsory Rental Pools:</strong> Being forced to hand over your keys to a management company (<em>Explotadora</em>).</li>
          <li><strong>Usage Restrictions:</strong> Being told you can only stay in your own property for a few weeks a year.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">New Regulations: Decree-Law 2/2025 and 2026 Trends</h2>
        <p class="mb-4">
          In 2025 and 2026, the Canary Islands government introduced new measures to address the "residentialization" of tourist zones. Many sellers in <strong>Corralejo (Fuerteventura)</strong> or <strong>Costa Teguise (Lanzarote)</strong> are now claiming their properties have <strong>"Consolidated Residential Use."</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          They may tell you that a <strong>Change of Use (Cambio de Uso)</strong> is "in progress." However, as a former government official, I advise extreme caution. A "pending" application is not a guarantee. Until the change is finalized by the <strong>Ayuntamiento</strong> (Town Hall) and registered at the <strong>Land Registry</strong>, your investment is at risk.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">Key Risks for Property Buyers in the Canaries</h2>
        <ol class="mb-4">
          <li class="mb-2"><strong>Mortgage Issues:</strong> Banks often cap lending at 50-60% for "tourist assets" compared to 80% for residential homes.</li>
          <li class="mb-2"><strong>Insurance Risks:</strong> Your policy may be void if you declare the property as a "dwelling" when it is legally a "commercial tourist unit."</li>
          <li class="mb-2"><strong>Resale Difficulty:</strong> Future buyers may be deterred by the lack of a <strong>Licence of First Occupation</strong> for residential use.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">How to Protect Your Canary Islands Investment</h2>
        <p class="mb-4">
          When <strong>buying property in the Canaries</strong>, your contract must be your shield. I ensure all my clients' contracts include a robust <strong>Rescission Clause</strong>. This allows you to walk away and recover your deposit if the <strong>Change of Use</strong> is not successfully registered within a specific timeframe.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-light p-4 rounded mb-5">
          <h3 class="h4 mb-3">Expert Legal Assistance Across the Islands</h3>
          <p class="mb-4">
            Don't let your "dream home" in the sun become a legal burden. Whether you are looking at <strong>real estate in Los Cristianos</strong>, <strong>Puerto del Carmen</strong>, or <strong>Caleta de Fuste</strong>, you need a specialist who understands the friction between municipal housing laws and regional tourism mandates.
          </p>
          <div class="text-center">
            <a href="#" data-bs-toggle="modal" data-bs-target="#contactModal" class="btn btn-lg rounded-pill" style="background-color: #b39c84; color: white;">
              Contact Roper Lawyers Today
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mb-5">
          <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Frequently Asked Questions:</h4>
          <div class="accordion" id="faqAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOne">
                  Can I live in a bungalow in Playa Blanca permanently?
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  It depends on the urban classification of the land. If it is "Suelo Turístico," permanent living may be prohibited even if you own the title deed.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo">
                  What is Decree-Law 2/2025 for Canary Islands property?
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  Decree-Law 2/2025 is a specific regulation introduced to address consolidated residential use in areas traditionally reserved for tourism.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree">
                  Why is my bank refusing a mortgage in a tourist complex?
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  Banks often view "tourist units" as commercial risks rather than residential homes, leading to lower valuation and lending caps.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

